				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: News from OOW perhaps...<a name="55046"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 4 04 5:17 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Pop was 55+, LoY for 40-60, LoDN for 20-65 (something for everybody). GoD for 50-70. Each expansion concentrated on one area. PoP and GoD both to hold the interest of the high end raiders. That's the primary focus, but there is still a lot there for the rest of us.
<br />

<br />
I've been spending most of my non-raiding time in GoD the past six weeks are so and it has many of great areas. The trials are like one group raids. They're hard at first but get easier with experience. I've seen a lot of spells drop there and some nice random drops. I have my first two spells and my shaman lucked out and got the first three. And I love the instanced zones. They're always there waiting for you. Nobody ever trains. Unless it's your puller. I've finished all six trials (bard and shaman) and I keep coming back for more. My only complaint is that casters should be able to bind nearby. You expect a few disasters when learning new areas, but the long run makes it tedious.
<br />

<br />
I've been working on the BiC (all but 2 drops for the first seven zones done). The quest reads much longer than it is so don't be put off. None of the drops are that rare. Play in those zones and you'll get them. Which is the thing about quests. They get you go to different places rather than sit in the secure spots you know. The ten keys and the Rwini event they trigger can be done by itself and I now have a nice new belt with FT3 and 2 aug slots.  Check it out: http://everquest.allakhazam.com/db/quest.html?quest=2870. BTW, we did this with a VT equipped guild group, so it is not out of reach.</span></td>
